\end{thm}

Let $x\in G$, and let $i=i(x)$ be the largest integer such
that $x\in D_i$. We denote by ${\tilde x}$ the 
element $xD_{i+1}\in L(G)$. Now, we can state one condition for ${\tilde x}$ to be ad-nilpotent.

\begin{lem} \label{4}(Lazard, \cite[page 131]{la}) 
For any $x\in G$ we have
$(ad\,{\tilde x})^q=ad\,(\widetilde {x^q})$.
\end{lem}

\begin{rem}
We note that $q$ in Lemma \ref{4} does not need to be a 
$p$-power. In fact, is easy to see that if $p^s$ is the 
maximal $p$-power dividing $q$, then $\tilde x$ is 
ad-nilpotent of index at most $p^s$.
\end{rem}

The following result is an immediate corollary of \cite[Theorem 1]{wize}.
\begin{lem}\label{2}
Let $G$ be any group satisfying a group-law. Then $L(G)$ is $PI$.
\end{lem}

